{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01YUbrHSTnKDK4xfbgmin19C","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see! ES is using Console (stdout) appender, not file appenders. So there are no log files in the logs directory (only GC logs).\n\nFor Filebeat to collect ES logs:\n- Option 1: Use Filebeat with Kubernetes autodiscover to read container stdout\n- Option 2: Configure ES to write to a file log (update log4j2.properties) and mount a shared volume\n\nThe simplest approach that doesn't require ES config changes would be to:\n1. Mount a shared emptyDir as the log volume\n2. Configure ES to write to files in that shared volume via log4j2 properties\n3. Have Filebeat read those files\n\nBut modifying ES's log4j2.properties requires a ConfigMap and rolling restart. For stack monitoring with sidecars, the cleaner approach is using Metricbeat to collect Elasticsearch metrics directly from localhost:9200, while Filebeat would need to read container logs from the host since it can't easily access another container's stdout from within a sidecar.\n\nFor a pure sidecar pattern to capture ES logs, I need to either mount a shared volume for logs, use a named pipe, or configure log4j2 to write to files. The best option is creating an emptyDir volume and a ConfigMap that directs Elasticsearch to write logs to that shared volume.\n\nBut I should verify whether the default log4j2 configuration already supports file logging or if I need to override it entirely.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1008,"cache_read_input_tokens":38174,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1008},"output_tokens":20,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d1d41423-0c6e-42cb-88b0-c36637753ff9","uuid":"