{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_014FzzPWr6CehdZk6ArXaPtv","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"So ES is using Console appenders (stdout). I need to:\n1. Override the log4j2.properties to write to files in a shared emptyDir\n2. Add a shared emptyDir for ES logs\n3. Add Metricbeat and Filebeat sidecars\n\nLet me plan the full solution:\n\n**For Metricbeat sidecar:**\n- Image: `docker.elastic.co/beats/metricbeat:7.17.9` (matches monitoring cluster)\n- Config: elasticsearch module, collect from localhost:9200 (HTTPS), ship to monitoring-es-http.monitoring:9200 (HTTP)\n- Needs CA cert mounted from es-http-tls secret and elastic password\n\n**For Filebeat sidecar:**\n- Image: `docker.elastic.co/beats/filebeat:7.17.9` (matches monitoring cluster)\n- Config: elasticsearch module, read from /var/log/elasticsearch/*.json, ship to monitoring ES\n- Needs a shared emptyDir volume where ES writes logs\n\nI'll need to create ConfigMaps for the log4j2.properties with file appenders, Metricbeat configuration, and Filebeat configuration, then update both sidecars to use them.\n\nFor the log4j2 approach, I need to think through the permissions carefully. Elasticsearch runs as uid 1000 and writes to `/usr/share/elasticsearch/logs`, which is already writable. I'll use a shared emptyDir so Filebeat can read the logs that Elasticsearch writes, with Filebeat running as root to handle the read permissions.\n\nMy plan is to update the log4j2 configuration to add RollingFile appenders that write JSON logs to a specific path alongside the existing Console appenders, then configure Metricbeat to collect metrics from the Elasticsearch node with proper authentication and SSL settings.\n\nI'm setting up Filebeat to read those JSON logs from the Elasticsearch module, but I need to reconsider how the Filebeat elasticsearch module expects the log files to be structured and named.\n\nSince Elasticsearch is currently writing to stdout rather than files, I need to either reconfigure Elasticsearch to write to files using log4j2.properties, or use a different Filebeat input approach. If I go with file-based logging, I'd need to mount a shared emptyDir volume at the logs directory so both the Elasticsearch container and Filebeat sidecar can access it.\n\nFor the version compatibility question between beats and the monitoring cluster, I should use beats that match the monitoring cluster version (7.17.9) since the monitoring APIs are stable across versions and beats 7.x can communicate with Elasticsearch 8.x REST APIs without issues. The REST API endpoints Metricbeat needs are all available in ES 8.x, but I need to handle the enforced TLS and authentication in 8.x by configuring those credentials in Metricbeat. My plan is to use both beats at 7.17.9 since they're compatible with the 8.x REST API and can ship to the 7.17.9 monitoring cluster. For the logs, I'll need to create a custom log4j2 configuration with file appenders and mount it into the container.\n\nI'm reconsidering the log4j2 approach—instead of replacing the default config, I'll write one that adds file appenders while preserving the existing console output so nothing breaks. Writing the log4j2 configuration...\n\nActually, I'm stepping back to think about whether I even need to modify log4j2 at all. Filebeat's Kubernetes autodiscover with pod annotations can capture container stdout directly, so maybe I'm overcomplicating this by trying to write to files.\n\nBut that approach requires mounting the host's container logs directory, which needs either a DaemonSet or elevated privileges. For a sidecar pattern where Filebeat runs in the same pod as Elasticsearch, the practical solution is to use a shared volume between them. I'll configure log4j2 to write to a RollingFile appender in a shared emptyDir, then have Filebeat read from there.\n\nOne issue though: the default `/usr/share/elasticsearch/logs` directory is owned by root, but Elasticsearch runs as uid 1000, so I'll need an initContainer to fix the permissions before the main container starts.\n\nActually, looking at the existing StatefulSet configuration, it already has `fsGroup: 1000` set, which means any volumes will be group-owned by GID 1000 and writable by the Elasticsearch user. So the emptyDir should work without needing an extra init step.\n\nNow I'm ready to write out the full solution with the ConfigMaps for the updated log4j2 configuration and Metricbeat settings. I'm deciding whether to keep console output alongside file logging for safety, or switch entirely to file appenders since Filebeat will handle the logs. I'll go with both appenders to avoid breaking anything, then configure the rolling file appender for the main server log.\n\nWriting log4j2 config... I'm adding the rolling file appender reference to the root logger so logs go to both console and file, then moving on to configure Metricbeat to collect Elasticsearch metrics like node stats and index data every 10 seconds using the configured credentials and SSL settings.\n\nNow I'm realizing the monitoring cluster is running 7.17.9, so I need to match that version with Metricbeat to ensure compatibility with the `.monitoring-es-*` indices and avoid API incompatibilities between 7.17.9 and ES 8.x. The REST APIs are backward compatible, so Metricbeat 7.17.9 should work fine collecting from ES 8.x. I'll go with both Metricbeat and Filebeat 7.17.9 for consistency. For the connection to ES 8.x, I need to handle the TLS requirement by referencing the CA certificate from the mounted volume and using the elastic user credentials from the secret. The Filebeat elasticsearch module will need to be configured to read from the appropriate log file paths.\n\nConfiguring Filebeat to use the elasticsearch module...\n\nNow I need to create the actual Kubernetes manifests. I'll set up ConfigMaps for the log4j2 configuration, metricbeat, and filebeat, then update the StatefulSet to moun