{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01TFsCK3nEDgLDuvyaQH8Kg6","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Zero filebeat documents found! So where did the 79 acked events go?\n\nWait - let me re-examine the Filebeat logs. Let me look at the initial startup logs more carefully:\n\n```\nINFO\ttemplate/load.go:110\tTemplate \"filebeat-7.17.9\" already exists and will not be overwritten.\nINFO\t[index-management]\tidxmgmt/std.go:297\tLoaded index template.\nINFO\t[publisher_pipeline_output]\tpipeline/output.go:151\tConnection to backoff(elasticsearch(http://monitoring-es-http.monitoring.svc.cluster.local:9200)) established\n```\n\nLooking at the metrics, 79 events were successfully acked by Elasticsearch. But that \"already exists\" message is suspicious - the template shouldn't have been there unless a previous Filebeat instance created it or something else provisioned it beforehand.\n\nSince all 5 pods are running Filebeat, the first one to start would create the template, and the rest would see it already exists. That explains it. But now I'm wondering where those 79 events actually went - if the template is `filebeat-7.17.9`, the index should be `filebeat-7.17.9-2026.06.24`, yet it doesn't show up. Maybe an ingest pipeline is routing them somewhere else, or the events are being tagged with module and dataset fields that change the index name.\n\nLooking at the index listing again, I notice `.ds-.logs-deprecation.elasticsearch-default-2026.06.24-000001` with 2 docs - that's a data stream index. Could Filebeat 7.17.9's elasticsearch module be using data streams? The module has a pipeline called `filebeat-7.17.9-elasticsearch-server-pipeline` that processes server logs, and it might be rerouting documents to a different index. Though reroute processors are an 8.x feature, so that seems unlikely in 7.17. Let me approach this differently and check what's actually happening with the indices.","signature":""