{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01P3jb4egTdGRF2TvjnhyuQW","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see! The ES 8.x log format does NOT have a `type` field. The pipeline drops logs where `elasticsearch.server.type != 'server'`. But after `json` parsing and `dot_expander`, the `elasticsearch.server.type` field won't exist. So the `drop` condition `ctx.elasticsearch.server.type != 'server'` evaluates to `true` (since the field is null/doesn't exist and null != 'server'), causing ALL documents to be dropped!\n\nThis is why there are no filebeat documents in the monitoring cluster. \n\nSo the root cause is that ES 8.x uses ECS format directly without the `type` field that existed in ES 7.x logs. I need to either create a custom ingest pipeline that handles the ES 8.x format properly, or switch to a Filebeat configuration that doesn't apply this problematic pipeline.\n\nSince the ES 8.x logs are already structured with parsed ECS fields like `elasticsearch.node.name` and `elasticsearch.cluster.name`, I should use a plain Filebeat input configuration instead of the Elasticsearch module, which was built for the older log format.\n\nThe cleanest solution is to configure Filebeat to read the JSON logs directly, decode them, and ship them to the monitoring cluster without relying on the problematic pipeline. I'm setting up a basic log input that points to the Elasticsearch server JSON log file.\n\nConfiguring Filebeat to decode the JSON at the source and add the necessary metadata fields, then output directly to the monitoring cluster's Elasticsearch instance. Since I'm bypassing the pipeline entirely, the events will be indexed with the JSON fields at the top level, which should preserve the ES 8.x log structure without any type-related filtering issues.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":862,"cache_read